<subSubSection id="C3396514FFEEC144FF4C706525857F43" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" type="description">
<paragraph id="8B9C369FFFEEC144FF4C706525857F43" blockId="7.[151,1437,578,2004]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
<emphasis id="B957EA8DFFEEC144FF4C706526407973" bold="true" box="[197,341,818,844]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Description</emphasis>
. Colony stolonal, with creeping, tortuous hydrohriza from which arise individual hydranths and gonophores. Perisarc thin, variably covering bases of hydranths, extending up 
<quantity id="4CDB9B7AFFEEC144FBE3700D23BA794B" box="[1130,1199,858,884]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" unit="mm" value="1.0">1 mm</quantity>
or more over body; perisarc generally infested with various microscopic algae, mainly diatoms. Hydranths much elongated, up to 
<quantity id="4CDB9B7AFFEEC144FF1E70FD27C879FB" box="[151,221,938,964]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.0" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" unit="mm" value="6.0">6 mm</quantity>
high in extension, nearly cylindrical, tapering imperceptibly but gradually towards hypostome; width 
<quantity id="4CDB9B7AFFEEC144FF1E7085263279D3" box="[151,295,978,1004]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.5" metricValueMax="4.0" metricValueMin="3.0" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" unit="mm" value="0.35" valueMax="0.4" valueMin="0.3">0.3–0.4 mm</quantity>
. Hypostome long, cylindrical, with rounded apex in relaxed hydranths, short and dome-shaped in contracted specimens. Hydranths with up to 
<number id="3DEB24B8FFEEC144FD2A70AD25D57E2B" box="[675,704,1018,1044]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" value="28.0">28</number>
tentacles; one whorl of 
<number id="3DEB24B8FFEEC144FC5470AD231F7E2B" box="[989,1034,1018,1044]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" value="5.0" valueMax="6.0" valueMin="4.0">4–6</number>
oral tentacles held vertically, plus 
<number id="3DEB24B8FFEEC144FF1E777527D67E03" box="[151,195,1058,1084]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" value="5.5" valueMax="6.0" valueMin="5.0">5–6</number>
additional, more or less distinct lower whorls, each with variably 
<number id="3DEB24B8FFEEC144FC45777524ED7E03" box="[972,1016,1058,1084]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" value="3.5" valueMax="5.0" valueMin="2.0">2–5</number>
tentacles attached obliquely to horizontally; whorls scattered over 
<number id="3DEB24B8FFEEC144FD97771D25387E5B" box="[542,557,1098,1124]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" value="2.0">2</number>
/ 
<number id="3DEB24B8FFEEC144FDBE771D25517E5B" box="[567,580,1098,1124]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" value="3.0">3</number>
of hydranth body; all tentacles filiform, length decreasing from distal towards proximal part of hydranth body; distal tentacles also more robust than proximal ones. 
<collectingCountry id="F334760FFFEEC144FA98772522587EB3" box="[1297,1357,1138,1164]" name="Malta" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Male</collectingCountry>
gonophores, sporosacs without radial canals, borne on hydrorhiza by means of short pedicels; covered by thin layer of slightly corrugated periderm; pear-shaped to ovate, tapering more abruptly at base and gradually from middle part towards apex. Female gonophores not seen. Nematocysts (undischarged capsules): microbasic euryteles (
<number id="3DEB24B8FFEEC144FF447645263D7F13" box="[205,296,1298,1324]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" value="7.15" valueMax="7.6" valueMin="6.7">6.7–7.6</number>
) × (
<number id="3DEB24B8FFEEC144FEEC764526D57F13" box="[357,448,1298,1324]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" value="2.7" valueMax="2.8" valueMin="2.6">2.6–2.8</number>
) µm (in tentacles and gonophores); desmonemes (
<number id="3DEB24B8FFEEC144FBB47645238C7F13" box="[1085,1177,1298,1324]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" value="4.9" valueMax="5.2" valueMin="4.6">4.6–5.2</number>
) × (
<number id="3DEB24B8FFEEC144FB5C764523EF7F13" box="[1237,1274,1298,1324]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" value="2.8">2.8</number>
–3.0) µm (in tentacles). Color: portion below hypostome and gonophore content reddish; gastrodermis of tentacle bases bright white; remaining of body translucid.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3396514FFEEC14BFF4C76DD27CD7B9D" lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="9" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8B9C369FFFEEC144FF4C76DD25047C53" blockId="7.[151,1437,578,2004]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
<emphasis id="B957EA8DFFEEC144FF4C76DD26227F9B" bold="true" box="[197,311,1418,1444]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Remarks</emphasis>
. 
<bibRefCitation id="EFB24B6EFFEEC144FECF76DD26E27F9B" author="Calder" box="[326,503,1418,1444]" pageId="7" pageNumber="49" refString="Calder, D. R. (1988 b) Shallow-water hydroids of Bermuda: the Athecatae. Royal Ontario Museum Life Sciences Contributions, 148, 1 - 107." type="journal article" year="1988" yearSuffix="b">
Calder (
<number id="3DEB24B8FFEEC144FE2A76DD26F57F9B" box="[419,480,1418,1444]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" value="1988.0">1988</number>
b)
</bibRefCitation>
introduced the new genus 
<taxonomicName id="4C234D1CFFEEC144FCA676DC24F77F9B" authority="Calder, 1988" authorityName="Calder" authorityYear="1988" box="[815,994,1419,1444]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Oceaniidae" genus="Rhizodendrium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anthoathecata" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B957EA8DFFEEC144FCA676DC24F77F9B" box="[815,994,1419,1444]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Rhizodendrium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in order to accommodate several species of 
<taxonomicName id="4C234D1CFFEEC144FF6576E4252B7FF3" authority="L. Agassiz, 1862" authorityName="L. Agassiz" authorityYear="1862" box="[236,574,1458,1484]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Oceaniidae" genus="Rhizogeton" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anthoathecata" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B957EA8DFFEEC144FF6576E426657FF3" box="[236,368,1459,1484]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Rhizogeton</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFB24B6EFFEEC144FEFE76E5252B7FF3" author="Agassiz" box="[375,574,1458,1484]" pageId="7" pageNumber="48" refString="Agassiz, L. (1862) Contributions to the Natural History of the United States of America. Second monograph, vol. 4. Little, Brown &amp; Co., Boston, 380 pp." type="book" year="1862">
L. Agassiz, 
<number id="3DEB24B8FFEEC144FD8A76E5252B7FF3" box="[515,574,1458,1484]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" value="1862.0">1862</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
with short, dome-shaped hypostome, more than 
<number id="3DEB24B8FFEEC144FBF276E5238D7FF3" box="[1147,1176,1458,1484]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" value="20.0">20</number>
tentacles (arranged in both a distinct, oral whorl and several additional lower, more or less distinct whorls), and spherical gonophores. These species were: 
<taxonomicName id="4C234D1CFFEEC144FE67755424757C23" authority="Broch, 1909" authorityName="Broch" authorityYear="1909" box="[494,864,1538,1564]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Oceaniidae" genus="Rhizogeton" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anthoathecata" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="nudus">
<emphasis id="B957EA8DFFEEC144FE67755425D47C23" box="[494,705,1539,1564]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Rhizogeton nudus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFB24B6EFFEEC144FD42755524757C23" author="Broch" box="[715,864,1538,1564]" pageId="7" pageNumber="49" refString="Broch, H. (1909) Die Hydroiden der Arktischen Meere. Fauna Arctica, 5, 129 - 247." type="journal article" year="1909">
Broch, 
<number id="3DEB24B8FFEEC144FCAA755524757C23" box="[803,864,1538,1564]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" value="1909.0">1909</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4C234D1CFFEEC144FCE6755422187C23" authority="Yamada, 1964" authorityName="Yamada" authorityYear="1964" box="[879,1293,1538,1564]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Oceaniidae" genus="Rhizogeton" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anthoathecata" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="ezoense">
<emphasis id="B957EA8DFFEEC144FCE6755423427C23" box="[879,1111,1539,1564]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Rhizogeton ezoense</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFB24B6EFFEEC144FBE8755522187C23" author="Yamada" box="[1121,1293,1538,1564]" pageId="7" pageNumber="54" refString="Yamada, M. (1964) Rhizogeton ezoense n. sp., a new hydroid from Hokkaido, Japan. Journal of the Faculty of Science, Hokkaido University, (6) 25, 395 - 397." type="journal article" year="1964">
Yamada, 
<number id="3DEB24B8FFEEC144FB59755522187C23" box="[1232,1293,1538,1564]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" value="1964.0">1964</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName id="4C234D1CFFEEC144FAC67554251F7C7B" authority="Calder, 1988" authorityName="Calder" authorityYear="1988" class="Hydrozoa" family="Oceaniidae" genus="Rhizodendrium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anthoathecata" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="sterreri">
<emphasis id="B957EA8DFFEEC144FAC6755426727C7B" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Rhizodendrium sterreri</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFB24B6EFFEEC144FEF9757D251F7C7B" author="Calder" box="[368,522,1578,1604]" pageId="7" pageNumber="49" refString="Calder, D. R. (1988 b) Shallow-water hydroids of Bermuda: the Athecatae. Royal Ontario Museum Life Sciences Contributions, 148, 1 - 107." type="journal article" year="1988" yearSuffix="b">
Calder, 
<number id="3DEB24B8FFEEC144FE44757D251F7C7B" box="[461,522,1578,1604]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" value="1988.0">1988</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
b. Following this point of view, only 
<taxonomicName id="4C234D1CFFEEC144FC4E757C22897C7B" authority="L. Agassiz, 1862" authorityName="L. Agassiz" authorityYear="1862" box="[967,1436,1578,1604]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Oceaniidae" genus="Rhizogeton" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anthoathecata" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="fusiformis">
<emphasis id="B957EA8DFFEEC144FC4E757C23DC7C7B" box="[967,1225,1579,1604]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Rhizogeton fusiformis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFB24B6EFFEEC144FB5B757D22897C7B" author="Agassiz" box="[1234,1436,1578,1604]" pageId="7" pageNumber="48" refString="Agassiz, L. (1862) Contributions to the Natural History of the United States of America. Second monograph, vol. 4. Little, Brown &amp; Co., Boston, 380 pp." type="book" year="1862">
L. Agassiz, 
<number id="3DEB24B8FFEEC144FAE8757D22897C7B" box="[1377,1436,1578,1604]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" value="1862.0">1862</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
could be retained in 
<taxonomicName id="4C234D1CFFEEC144FE0F7504251F7C53" box="[390,522,1619,1644]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Oceaniidae" genus="Rhizogeton" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anthoathecata" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B957EA8DFFEEC144FE0F7504251F7C53" box="[390,522,1619,1644]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Rhizogeton</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B9C369FFFEEC144FF4C752D26C37CDB" blockId="7.[151,1437,578,2004]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
However, the available 
<typeStatus id="5498883DFFEEC144FE54752D25057CAB" box="[477,528,1658,1684]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">type</typeStatus>
material of 
<taxonomicName id="4C234D1CFFEEC144FD29752C240C7CAB" authority="Calder, 1988" authorityName="Calder" authorityYear="1988" box="[672,793,1659,1684]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Oceaniidae" genus="Rhizodendrium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anthoathecata" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="sterreri">
<emphasis id="B957EA8DFFEEC144FD29752C240C7CAB" box="[672,793,1659,1684]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">R. sterreri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was relatively scarce (two colonies on 
<taxonomicName id="4C234D1CFFEEC144FB65752C227E7CAB" box="[1260,1387,1659,1684]" class="Phaeophyceae" family="Sargassaceae" genus="Sargassum" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fucales" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Heterokontophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B957EA8DFFEEC144FB65752C227E7CAB" box="[1260,1387,1659,1684]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Sargassum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp., see 
<bibRefCitation id="EFB24B6EFFEEC144FF4A75F526767C83" author="Calder" box="[195,355,1698,1724]" pageId="7" pageNumber="49" refString="Calder, D. R. (1988 b) Shallow-water hydroids of Bermuda: the Athecatae. Royal Ontario Museum Life Sciences Contributions, 148, 1 - 107." type="journal article" year="1988" yearSuffix="b">
Calder 
<number id="3DEB24B8FFEEC144FE9075F526407C83" box="[281,341,1698,1724]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" value="1988.0">1988</number>
b
</bibRefCitation>
) and sterile. Therefore, no thorough comparison with its congeners could be made when the species was first described.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B9C369FFFEEC14BFF4C75A524507AE5" blockId="7.[151,1437,578,2004]" lastBlockId="8.[151,1436,152,458]" lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="9" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
The examination of the present material showed that the mature (male) gonophores of 
<taxonomicName id="4C234D1CFFEEC144FB3575A422217D33" authority="Calder, 1988" authorityName="Calder" authorityYear="1988" box="[1212,1332,1779,1804]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Oceaniidae" genus="Rhizodendrium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anthoathecata" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="sterreri">
<emphasis id="B957EA8DFFEEC144FB3575A422217D33" box="[1212,1332,1779,1804]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">R. sterreri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are fusiform rather than spherical, and therefore different from those of its congeners. Some additional inconsistencies are also illustrated by two other species, as follows. The hydranths of 
<taxonomicName id="4C234D1CFFEEC144FBAD741427C77DBB" authority="Schuchert, 1996" authorityName="Schuchert" authorityYear="1996" class="Hydrozoa" family="Oceaniidae" genus="Rhizogeton" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anthoathecata" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="conicum">
<emphasis id="B957EA8DFFEEC144FBAD741422007D63" box="[1060,1301,1859,1884]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Rhizogeton conicum</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFB24B6EFFEEC144FA96741527C77DBB" author="Schuchert" pageId="7" pageNumber="52" refString="Schuchert, P. (1996) The marine fauna of New Zealand: athecate hydroids and their medusae (Cnidaria: Hydrozoa). New Zealand Oceanographic Institute Memoir, 106, 1 - 159." type="journal article" year="1996">
Schuchert, 
<number id="3DEB24B8FFEEC144FF1E743D27C77DBB" box="[151,210,1898,1924]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" value="1996.0">1996</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
have up to 
<number id="3DEB24B8FFEEC144FEEE743D26917DBB" box="[359,388,1898,1924]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" value="20.0">20</number>
tentacles, and its gonophores are spherical. A likely new record of 
<taxonomicName id="4C234D1CFFEEC144FB36743C224D7DBB" box="[1215,1368,1899,1924]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Oceaniidae" genus="Rhizogeton" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anthoathecata" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="fusiformis">
<emphasis id="B957EA8DFFEEC144FB36743C224D7DBB" box="[1215,1368,1899,1924]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">R. fusiformis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry id="F334760FFFEEC144FF1E74C527CA7D93" box="[151,223,1938,1964]" name="South Korea" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Korea</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFB24B6EFFEEC144FF6474C5267E7D93" author="Park" box="[237,363,1938,1964]" pageId="7" pageNumber="52" refString="Park, J. H. (1997) Four athecate hydroids from Korean waters. Korean Journal of Systematic Zoology, 13 (2), 83 - 92." type="journal article" year="1997">
Park 
<number id="3DEB24B8FFEEC144FEA574C5267E7D93" box="[300,363,1938,1964]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" value="1997.0">1997</number>
</bibRefCitation>
), proved that the number of tentacles per hydranth could be as much as 
<number id="3DEB24B8FFEEC144FB3874C523E87D93" box="[1201,1277,1938,1964]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" value="18.0" valueMax="20.0" valueMin="16.0">16–20</number>
, not only 
<number id="3DEB24B8FFEEC144FAF974C527A17DEB" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" value="11.0" valueMax="12.0" valueMin="10.0">10– 12</number>
as in the original description given by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFB24B6EFFEEC144FDF774ED24407DEB" author="Agassiz" box="[638,853,1978,2004]" pageId="7" pageNumber="48" refString="Agassiz, L. (1862) Contributions to the Natural History of the United States of America. Second monograph, vol. 4. Little, Brown &amp; Co., Boston, 380 pp." type="book" year="1862">
L. Agassiz (
<number id="3DEB24B8FFEEC144FC8574ED24597DEB" box="[780,844,1978,2004]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" value="1862.0">1862</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
. This difference is most probably due to a combination of both geographical and ecological factors. Therefore, the tentacle number in these hydroids should not be regarded as having a great taxonomical importance.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B9C369FFFE1C14BFF4C73BF24527B15" blockId="8.[151,1436,152,458]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">
Taken together, these facts suggest the inappropriateness of the genus 
<taxonomicName id="4C234D1CFFE1C14BFB9A73BF23D37B3E" authority="Calder, 1988" authorityName="Calder" authorityYear="1988" box="[1043,1222,232,257]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Oceaniidae" genus="Rhizodendrium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anthoathecata" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B957EA8DFFE1C14BFB9A73BF23D37B3E" box="[1043,1222,232,257]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Rhizodendrium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which should be included in the synonymy of 
<taxonomicName id="4C234D1CFFE1C14BFE64724724577B15" authority="L. Agassiz, 1862" authorityName="L. Agassiz" authorityYear="1862" box="[493,834,272,298]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Oceaniidae" genus="Rhizogeton" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anthoathecata" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B957EA8DFFE1C14BFE64724725647B16" box="[493,625,272,297]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Rhizogeton</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFB24B6EFFE1C14BFDF0724724577B15" author="Agassiz" box="[633,834,272,298]" pageId="8" pageNumber="48" refString="Agassiz, L. (1862) Contributions to the Natural History of the United States of America. Second monograph, vol. 4. Little, Brown &amp; Co., Boston, 380 pp." type="book" year="1862">
L. Agassiz, 
<number id="3DEB24B8FFE1C14BFC8D724724577B15" box="[772,834,272,298]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" value="1862.0">1862</number>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B9C369FFFE1C14BFF4C726F27CD7B9D" blockId="8.[151,1436,152,458]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">
Although originally found on pelagic 
<taxonomicName id="4C234D1CFFE1C14BFD08726F24157B6E" box="[641,768,312,337]" class="Phaeophyceae" family="Sargassaceae" genus="Sargassum" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Fucales" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Heterokontophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B957EA8DFFE1C14BFD08726F24157B6E" box="[641,768,312,337]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Sargassum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation id="EFB24B6EFFE1C14BFC99726F24A17B6D" author="Calder" box="[784,948,312,338]" pageId="8" pageNumber="49" refString="Calder, D. R. (1988 b) Shallow-water hydroids of Bermuda: the Athecatae. Royal Ontario Museum Life Sciences Contributions, 148, 1 - 107." type="journal article" year="1988" yearSuffix="b">
Calder 
<number id="3DEB24B8FFE1C14BFCEE726F24B07B6D" box="[871,933,312,338]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" value="1988.0">1988</number>
b
</bibRefCitation>
), 
<taxonomicName id="4C234D1CFFE1C14BFC41726F23557B6E" authority="Calder, 1988" authorityName="Calder" authorityYear="1988" box="[968,1088,312,337]" class="Hydrozoa" family="Oceaniidae" genus="Rhizodendrium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Anthoathecata" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="sterreri">
<emphasis id="B957EA8DFFE1C14BFC41726F23557B6E" box="[968,1088,312,337]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">R. sterreri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was presently found growing on a variety of substrates: algae, sponges, crevices in both scleractinians and hydrocorals, and mineral concretions.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
